data.content:
Here's the xUnit equivalent:

**1. `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`** → constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose()`
**2. `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`** → `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture class

```csharp
// Shared fixture handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // was [OneTimeSetUp]
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // was [OneTimeTearDown]
    }
}

// No [TestFixture] attribute needed in xUnit
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]                           // was [Test]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);                  // was Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);      // was Assert.That(x, Is.EqualTo(y))
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[TestFixture]` | *(nothing)* |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |
| `[SetUp]` | constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` constructor |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | fixture's `Dispose` |

If your setup/teardown is async, implement `IAsyncLifetime` (with `InitializeAsync`/`DisposeAsync`) instead of using the constructor and `IDisposable`.
